body:
Given the following code in `show_task_err.rs`:

``` rust
#![feature(if_let)]

use std::any::{Any, AnyRefExt};
use std::intrinsics::{TypeId, type_id};
use std::task;

fn main() {
    match task::try(proc() {
        let msg = "Oh noes!";
        panic!(msg);
    }) {
        Ok(()) => (),
        Err(err) => {
            println!("err.get_type_id(): {}", err.get_type_id());
            println!("type_id &str: {}", unsafe { type_id::<&str>() });
            println!("TypeId &str: {}", TypeId::of::<&str>());
            if let Some(msg) = err.downcast_ref::<&str>() {
                println!("Err str: {}", msg);
            }
            else {
                println!("Err unknown");
            }
        }
    }
}

/* Output of: rustc -v verbose; rustc show_task_err.rs; .\show_task_err.exe

rustc 0.13.0-nightly (0a5e7f359 2014-11-03 23:16:55 +0000)
binary: rustc
commit-hash: 0a5e7f35949d18f312dca90af73e56aced6f2b0e
commit-date: 2014-11-03 23:16:55 +0000
host: i686-w64-mingw32
release: 0.13.0-nightly
task '<unnamed>' panicked at 'Oh noes!', show_task_err.rs:10
err.get_type_id(): TypeId { t: 2347986002194018685 }
type_id &str: TypeId { t: 11265961301656644907 }
TypeId &str: TypeId { t: 11265961301656644907 }
Err str: Oh noes!

*/
```

Gives the output as commented.  As you can see, despite the Any _clearly_ containing a `&str`, `Any::get_type_id` returns a completely different `TypeId` than either `TypeId::of` or `type_id` do.

Whilst one can still do downcasting with the provided API, the discrepancy is still really weird.  There doesn't appear to be anything in the documentation to explain this, either.
